The paper deals with geometric decision problems and graph recognition, which are typical topics in computational geometry (cs.CG) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The use of transmission graphs and the complexity class $\exists \mathbb{R}$ suggest that the paper may also be relevant to theoretical computer science (cs.CC) and algorithms (cs.DS). Finally, the application of the results to networks of directional antennas may indicate a connection to machine learning (cs.LG).
